## Mobile architecture direction

### 8. Mobile app remains a client, not the whole system
The Android app should be:
- a practical front end
- a fast daily-use control surface
- a sync-aware client for Ember systems

It should not become:
- the only place data exists
- the only way the user interacts with Ember
- a giant pile of mixed UI/business logic sludge

### 9. Preferred phased approach
Saved longer-term direction:
- Phase 1: Android client connected to current backend
- Phase 2: local utility layer for time/reminders/log caching/offline queue
- Phase 3: optional small offline local model fallback
- Phase 4: fuller assistant/mobile integrations

### 10. Cross-device Ember sync is later work
Keep this out of near-term mobile priorities for now.

Not current priority:
- mobile ↔ desktop sync
- generalized cross-device Ember sync

Reason:
- Health Connect is now in place as the first meaningful sync target
- backup/export handles portability for now
- don’t build transport plumbing before the data story is mature

---

## Workflow / process rules for mobile work

### 11. One actionable step at a time
- one step at a time unless no feedback is needed

### 12. Build/version rule
- app version = shared release line
- build number = active PR number during pre-v1 work
- example: PR41 should use version `0.3`, build `41`

### 13. Real-device testing wins
- device behavior overrides simulator assumptions
- user testing feedback overrides “the code looks right”

### 14. Keep fixes local when obvious
- for small obvious code fixes, fix directly instead of punting everything to Copilot

